== Description {{<a name="description"></a>}}

BASIS-14 will be a full day tutorial covering the current state-of-the-art in
linear and nonlinear image and surface analysis techniques. Our aim is to
provide attendees with a clear understanding of the theory and practice in
this area by developing a unified treatment in terms of basis-based
expansions.

Starting with the fundamentals of linear image processing, we will see how the
main notions of Fourier transforms can be understood in terms of a change of
basis, and use this intuition to explore its multifold ramifications and
extensions to nonlinear image processing and surface analysis.

In particular we will cover the range of techniques developed around sparse
coding with overcomplete dictionaries, involving optimization with sparsity
inducing norms, dictionary learning, exemplar and patch-based representations,
and non-local modeling. We will discuss the notions of scale and invariance in
this setting and draw connections with classic multi-resolution approaches and
recent developments in deep learning.

Turning to 3D shape processing and analysis, we will build on the intuition
developed around Fourier analysis in Euclidean spaces and heat diffusion on
images, and discuss how the same notions generalize to non-Euclidean spaces
(surfaces), through the development of heat diffusion on surfaces by means of
the Laplace-Beltrami operator and its spectral decomposition. We will show
applications in finding correspondence and similarity between deformable
shapes, local and global feature descriptors, shape filtering and editing. 

We will illustrate the importance of the techniques with applications spanning
both classical image processing problems, such as denoising and deblurring but
also cutting-edge computer vision problems involving image classification,
object detection, shape retrieval and surface registration, among others.


